<p>These original coolers were very successful and after the initial
development work by this department, the Department of Engineering
Science in Oxford, and the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, the bulk of
the technology was transferred to British Aerospace. The use of
mechanical coolers in space was pioneered by this programme, and of
the many which are now routinely used in space, only a few are not
derivatives of the original Oxford design. An example of such a
'derivative' is the <a
href="http://www.ball.com/aerospace/pdf/cryosys.pdf">Ball Aerospace and
Technologies Corporation Cryocooler</a> on the HIRDLS instrument
(Fig&#160;3) which was recently <a
href="../../hirdls/home.htm">calibrated</a> at Oxford.</p>

<p>Since the transfer of the technology to industry the department has
maintained a small presence in the field with further research into Pulse
Tube Coolers and single unit Stirling cycle coolers for deep-space
missions.</p>

